  "Idea": "The proposed idea introduces 'Neuro-Symbolic Concept Refinement via Mutual Alignment over Evolving Hierarchies' (NSCR-ME), a novel framework that rethinks hierarchical concept expansion as a dynamic, iterative dialogue between symbolic knowledge and neural representations. Rather than treating knowledge graphs (KGs) as static sources of facts or inducing soft hierarchies purely from embeddings, NSCR-ME establishes a dual-track architecture: a symbolic track grounded in lightweight description logic (DL) ontologies derived from KGs, and a neural track composed of contextualized graph transformers operating over document-grounded subgraphs. These tracks interact through a mutual alignment mechanism that ensures any contextual expansion of a concept (e.g., inferring that 'climate policy' includes 'carbon pricing' in a given article) must satisfy both semantic plausibility (neural confidence) and logical consistency (symbolic satisfiability). At the core of NSCR-ME is the Evolving Hierarchy Engine (EHE), which maintains a long-term conceptual memory as a probabilistic taxonomy updated via belief revision rules. For each input context (e.g., a news article), EHE first retrieves relevant concepts and induces a context-specific temporary hierarchy using a sparse matrix-tree variational inference module (as in Paper 2), then initiates bidirectional refinement: (1) The neural track performs context-aware message passing to enrich node representations with syntactic, discourse, and relational features; (2) The symbolic track evaluates these enriched nodes against DL-based integrity constraints (e.g., subsumption, disjointness) extracted from the KG; (3) A conflict resolver identifies inconsistencies (e.g., assigning 'vegetarian restaurant' as serving 'beef stew') and triggers targeted re-encoding or pruning. Crucially, plausible expansions are fed back into the long-term hierarchy via a gated belief update mechanism, allowing the system to evolve its conceptual understanding over time—e.g., gradually recognizing 'remote work' as a subclass of 'employment arrangements' after repeated exposure. To support interpretability, NSCR-ME generates justification paths linking expanded attributes to both textual evidence and symbolic axioms. The model is trained using a multi-objective loss combining reconstruction accuracy, logical consistency (measured via satisfiability in DL reasoners), and downstream task performance (e.g., NLI, QA). By integrating neuro-symbolic feedback loops and modeling conceptual evolution, NSCR-ME enables not only more accurate and coherent concept expansion but also provides auditable reasoning trails—a critical advantage for high-stakes applications like scientific literature synthesis or legal analysis.",
